f=Shared OS/logical/aaker-brand-equity.md · in=David Aaker's *Building Strong Brands* (1996) foundational academic work brand equity. While Ogilvy (1963) articulated *intuition* brands valuable assets beyond their physical products "Every advertisement thought contribution complex symbol brand image" Aaker provided *architecture*: measurable, multi-dimensional model what brand equity build it. Aaker defines brand equity as: **"A set assets liabilities linked brand's name symbol add subtract value provided product service firm and/or firm's customers."** (Ch.1, p.7-8). extraction operationalizes dimension Brand Studio's measurement, strategy, creative functions. · h2:PART BRAND IDENTITY SYSTEM=*Ch.2, pp.26-33* Aaker's original contribution brand strategy Brand Identity System structured framework defining what brand STANDS FOR. distinct brand image (what consumers currently perceive); identity what brand ASPIRES be. · h3:2.1 Four Identity Perspectives (Ch.2, pp.28-32)=**1. Brand Product (Ch.2, pp.28-29):** Product scope, product attributes, quality/value, uses, users, country origin. common identity perspective brand defined product sells. Volvo safe cars. Rolex precision watches. Kleenex tissue. **2. Brand Organization (Ch.2, pp.29-30):** Organizational attributes (innovation, consumer concern, trustworthiness), local vs. global. brand defined organization behind it. Patagonia environmental activism. Google "Don't evil" (originally). perspective harder competitors copy you reverse-engineer product; you cannot reverse-engineer organizational culture. **3. Brand Person (Ch.2, pp.30-31):** Brand personality (sincere, exciting, competent, sophisticated, rugged), brand-customer relationships. brand defined human personality. Apple creative, rebellious. Harley-Davidson rugged, freedom-seeking. Dove caring, authentic. emotionally resonant identity perspective. **4. Brand Symbol (Ch.2, pp.31-32):** Visual imagery metaphors, brand heritage. brand defined visual symbolic elements. Nike's swoosh, McDonald's golden arches, Coca-Cola's contour bottle. Three components: · h3:2.1 Four Identity Perspectives (Ch.2, pp.28-32)=**Visual imagery:** Logo, color palette, typography, photography style, design language., **Metaphors:** brand's symbolic meaning. Nike victory (named Greek goddess). Amazon vastness, endless selection (named river)., **Brand heritage:** story brand came from. Levi's original jeans, 1853 Gold Rush. Hermes French craftsmanship since 1837. · h3:2.2 Identity vs. Image (Ch.2, pp.32-33)=Aaker clarifies critical distinction: · h3:2.2 Identity vs. Image (Ch.2, pp.32-33)=**Brand Identity:** What organization WANTS brand stand for. Aspirational. Created brand owner., **Brand Image:** What consumers currently PERCEIVE brand stand for. Current reality. Created touchpoints., **The gap between Identity Image strategic problem.** gap large, marketing communication failing convey intended identity. · h2:PART DISTINCTIVE ASSETS=*Ch.8, pp.196-228* · h3:4.1 What Distinctive Assets?=Aaker's concept distinctive assets later popularized Byron Sharp (2010, *How Brands Grow*) "distinctive brand assets" sensory shortcuts trigger brand recognition without conscious processing. **Types distinctive assets (Ch.8, pp.200-212):** · h3:4.1 What Distinctive Assets?=\| Asset Type \| Definition \| Examples \| · h3:4.1 What Distinctive Assets?=\|-----------\|-----------\|----------\| · h3:4.1 What Distinctive Assets?=\| **Logos** \| Visual identity marks \| Nike swoosh, Apple apple, McDonald's golden arches \| · h3:4.1 What Distinctive Assets?=\| **Colors** \| Owned color(s) \| Tiffany blue, Coca-Cola red, UPS brown, T-Mobile magenta \| · h3:4.1 What Distinctive Assets?=\| **Taglines/Sonic** \| Auditory signatures \| "I'm Lovin' It" + the McD jingle, Intel's sonic logo \| · h3:4.1 What Distinctive Assets?=\| **Characters/Mascots** \| Brand personas \| Michelin Man, Tony the Tiger, GEICO gecko \| · h3:4.1 What Distinctive Assets?=\| **Packaging shapes** \| Product silhouette \| Coca-Cola contour bottle, Toblerone triangle, Absolut bottle \| · h3:4.1 What Distinctive Assets?=\| **Typography** \| Owned typefaces \| Coca-Cola Spencerian script, Disney's whimsical font \| · h3:4.1 What Distinctive Assets?=\| **Spokespeople** \| Human faces of the brand \| Flo (Progressive), Colonel Sanders (KFC), Matthew McConaughey (Lincoln) \| · h3:4.1 What Distinctive Assets?=\| **Scents** \| Olfactory signatures \| Abercrombie & Fitch store scent, Singapore Airlines cabin scent \| · h3:4.2 Distinctive Asset Heuristics (Ch.8, pp.214-222)=Aaker's rules building protecting distinctive assets: **Fame over differentiation:** valuable distinctive assets famous (recognized majority), merely different. unique asset nobody sees worthless. **Consistency over novelty:** "The brands strongest distinctive assets maintained them minimal modification decades. Coca-Cola's script logo introduced 1887." **Link brand, category:** "If consumers see asset think 'cola' rather 'Coca-Cola,' it's distinctive asset it's category cue." **Multi-sensory possible:** powerful assets work across senses. "Intel's sonic logo visual logo 'Intel Inside' tagline multi-sensory distinctive asset." · h3:4.3 Distinctive Asset Inventory Check (Ch.8, pp.222-228)=Aaker recommends periodic audit: "Can consumers identify brand asset isolation?" asset, test: · h3:4.3 Distinctive Asset Inventory Check (Ch.8, pp.222-228)=**Fame:** What category's buyers recognize asset?, **Uniqueness:** What correctly attribute brand (vs. competitors)?, **Linkage:** linked BRAND CATEGORY? · h3:4.3 Distinctive Asset Inventory Check (Ch.8, pp.222-228)=**Connection Binet Field:** Creative Commitment (Binet Field, Ch.7) mechanism builds distinctive assets. brand changes visual identity annually never gives asset time become distinctive. Binet Field: "Campaigns running core creative idea years show 40% higher effectiveness." effectiveness premium comes partly distinctive asset effect. · h3:Brand Equity Health Score=brand Brand Studio's portfolio, score four equity dimensions (scale 0-10): · h3:Brand Equity Health Score=\| Dimension \| Measurement \| Weight \| Score \| · h3:Brand Equity Health Score=\|-----------\|------------\|--------\|-------\| · h3:Brand Equity Health Score=\| **Awareness** \| Unaided recall in target market + aided recognition \| 25% \| /10 \| · h3:Brand Equity Health Score=\| **Associations** \| Strength + favorability + uniqueness of top 3 associations \| 30% \| /10 \| · h3:Brand Equity Health Score=\| **Perceived Quality** \| Consumer perception rating vs. actual product quality rating \| 25% \| /10 \| · h3:Brand Equity Health Score=\| **Loyalty** \| Repurchase rate + NPS + share of wallet \| 20% \| /10 \| · h3:Brand Equity Health Score=\| **Total** \| \| 100% \| /40 \| · h3:Brand Equity Health Score=**Score interpretation:** · h3:Brand Equity Health Score=36-40: STRONG BRAND EQUITY. brand moated asset. Protect; invest maintaining., 28-35: BUILDING BRAND EQUITY. brand foundation. Invest weakest dimension., 18-27: WEAK BRAND EQUITY. brand risk commoditization. Immediate remediation needed., 0-17: BRAND EQUITY. product name brand. Start awareness. · h3:Distinctive Asset Inventory Audit=distinctive asset, score: **Fame:** target market recognizes asset (Target: >70%) **Uniqueness:** who correctly attribute YOUR brand, competitors category (Target: >80%) **Consistency:** Years consistent use (Target: years Binet Field) **Multi-sensory:** Number senses asset engages (Target: flagship assets) · h2:BOUNDARIES WITH OTHER SCRIPTS=**brand_metrics.py:** Implements brand awareness score (aided/unaided recall), brand association strength calculator (Riess Trout word ownership), NPS-style loyalty categorizer, share-of-voice calculator, ESOV calculator, 60:40 budget allocator, distinctive asset inventory checker extraction., **marketing_laws.py:** Aaker's dimensions operationalize Cialdini's persuasion principles (Authority Perceived Quality; Social Proof Loyalty; Liking Associations), Ries Trout's positioning (Focus Dominant Association; Mind Awareness; Perception Perceived Quality), Zajonc's Mere Exposure Effect (Awareness)., **ogilvy-creative-code.md:** Ogilvy's brand image concept historical foundation; Aaker's four dimensions operational framework. Ogilvy rule contributes one Aaker dimensions., **binet-field-effectiveness.md:** 60:40 brand-building budget investment Aaker's four dimensions. Brand-building awareness associations perceived quality; activation converting loyalty sales.